 <hr align="left" color="#000000" size="1"/>
 <p>
  MUCH / "a lot"
 </p>
 <p>
  <img border="0" height="241" src="../../signjpegs/m/much.h1.jpg" width="300"/>
  <img border="0" height="241" src="../../signjpegs/m/much.h2.jpg" width="300"/>
  <img border="0" height="241" src="../../signjpegs/m/much.h3.jpg" width="300"/>
 </p>
 <font face="Arial">
  <br/>
  Some things are not "countable." For example you can’t count “water.” You can 
  count “cups of water,” or “drops of water” but you can’t
  <i>
   count
  </i>
  water.
  <br/>
  <br/>
  When discussing things that are not “countable,” I recommend you use the sign “MUCH 
  / a lot” (volume).
  <br/>
  <br/>
  Sample sentence:
  <br/>
  YOUR FRENCH-FRIES, YOU SALT A-LOT? (Do you like a lot of salt on 
			your French fries?)
  <br/>
  <br/>
